<h2 id="event">Significant weather events</h2>
<h3 id="lucifer">Heat wave 'Lucifer' in southern Europe</h3>
In early autumn 2017, Europe is recovering from the soaring temperatures during the 2017 summer 'Lucifer' heat wave. Especially southern Europe saw the effects of this heat wave. Figure 1 (left panel) shows for this summer the largest number of consecutive days where the daily maximum temperature was above the 90th percentile - the Warm Spell Duration Index. The right panel of Figure 1 shows the precipitation in summer 2017 as a fraction of the climatological mean amount. It shows the dry conditions in all European countries around the Mediterranean, the Balkan and into the Ukraine.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_heat_wave_duration_index_wrt_mean_of_reference_period_baselayers_overlay_2017-08-31T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_heat_wave_duration_index_wrt_mean_of_reference_period_baselayers_overlay_2017-08-31T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc__2017-08-31T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_HWDI_2017_nc__2017-08-31T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_rr_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_rr_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc__2017-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_rr_EOBS_2017summer_relative_nc__2017-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Shown is the Warm Spell Duration Index (WSDI, left panel) and the fraction of precipitation with respect to the 1981-2010 climatology (right panel). The WSDI is defined as the number of consecutive days in the summer (June, July, August) of 2017 where the daily maximum temperature is higher than the (locally defined) 90th percentile. This reference value is calculated for a five day window centred on each calendar day of a given 30 year climate reference period.</em>
<br><br>
In summer 2017 temperatures were mostly above the long term mean with a maximum of more than +5 &#176;C over the Balkans and Spain. Scandinavia showed the lowest temperature anomalies. Portugal was hot - it saw the 9th hottest summer since 1931 - and extremely dry - the 3rd driest on record. Two heat waves were observed in Portugal. Temperatures in Spain this summer reached the second rank (since 1956, after 2003) with a deviation of +1.6 &#176;C above the average of 1981-2010. Spain and France reported five heat waves for this summer. Most of Italy was also affected by heat waves and the drought in southern and central Italy persisted to one year and water reservoirs were getting empty. The drought and water shortage increased the number of wild fires and reduced the agricultural yields, which was also the case on the Balkan peninsula, where summer air temperature in Croatia were +2.4 to +4.0 &#176;C higher than usual. Serbia saw its second warmest summer on record with highest daily maximum temperature of 41.6 &#176;Ð¡ on 6 August and six recorded heat waves. Slovakia reported two heat waves where in Bratislava summer air temperature was the 2nd highest since 1931. Summer was also hot in the Republic of Moldova, where August temperatures reached +39 &#176;Ð¡ - a once in 15 year value. While the recorded summer temperatures in the Republic of Moldova are observed about once every 10 years for the entire observation period, these temperatures are now more frequently occurring on average of once every 3 years. 
<br><br>
Focusing on south west Europe (10W-15E/36N-45N - excluding the Balkan area), the 2017 heat wave is comparable in length and fierceness to the September 2016, July 1982 and August 2012 heat waves, while the latter affected a larger area than the 'Lucifer' heat wave (Figure 2).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/2017/rcc_eude_swe_ttt_hw_bub_aktuell.png"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/rcc_eude_swe_ttt_hw_bub_aktuell.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Severity of heat wave 'Lucifer' with respect to other heat waves in the past. The severity in this bubble-plot has been determined over south west Europe.</em>
<br><br>
The long and hot summer southern Europe experienced in 2017 is illustrated in Figure 3 showing the maximum value of the daily maximum temperature for 2017. It shows that in large areas around the Mediterranean the hottest summer day was close to or even exceeded 40 &#176;С. Looking at a somewhat less extreme metric for the heat of the summer, Figure 4 shows the number of Summer Days (where the daily maximum temperature exceed 25 &#176;С) as a deviation from the 1981-2010 climatological mean. This figure shows that in a broad band from Portugal and Spain, over France and the Low Countries, into the Balkan Peninsula and west Russia, the number of Summer Days was higher than usual. Figure 5 shows the maximum number of Consecutive Summer Days, which reflects the length of the period with summer temperatures. This figure shows that mainly around the Mediterranean, the period with summer temperatures was much longer than usual.
<br><br>
