<h2 id="temperature">Temperature</h2>
<h3 id="annualtemp">Annual mean air temperature</h3>
Surface air temperatures are measured at an extensive network of stations in Europe. These data are collected and aggregated into a European temperature. The annual mean values in this <a href="https://www.ecad.eu/eobs" target="_blank">E-OBS</a> dataset are presented in Figure 6 for the land area between between 34&#176;-71&#176;N and 25&#176;W-40&#176;E with the dark blue and red bars. The same is shown for ERA-Interim with light blue and red bars.
<br><br>
The grey bars (E-OBS only) in the top panel indicate the estimated uncertainties which take into account the errors introduced by spatial interpolation over areas without observation stations, inhomogeneities in the temperature data that result from station relocations / changes in measurement instruments etc., and biases due to urbanisation, as documented in Van der Schrier et al. (2013) and Chrysanthou et al. (2014). The uncertainties tell us that although we are not 100% certain about the ranking of individual years, the overall positive trend since the 1980s is very pronounced.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/2017/EuropeanAverage_annual_ERA_EOBS_2017_wrt81-10_until1231.png"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/EuropeanAverage_annual_ERA_EOBS_2017_wrt81-10_until1231.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/2017/dailyanomalies_2017_v16.0.png"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/dailyanomalies_2017_v16.0.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 6: European land surface temperature: annual anomalies. The grey bands show the uncertainty in the averaged temperature (top). Daily anomalies with respect to the seasonal cycle for 2017 (bottom, E-OBS only). E-OBS v16.0 and ERA-Interim</em>
<br><br>
The table below shows the ranking of the top 10 years in both E-OBS as ERA-Interim. As mentioned above, the uncertainties tell us that the ranking of individual years are not 100% certain. But it is clear that 2017 is in the top 5 of warmest years, but not the warmest on record, in both datasets.
