<h3 id="seasontemp">Seasonal mean air temperature</h3>
Seasonal temperature anomaly patterns (Figure 8, middel panels) shifted substantially between winter and spring and between summer and autumn in 2017. Winter 2017 (the period from December 2016 to February 2017) was characterized by relatively warm conditions in the north, and relatively cold conditions in the south-east and far east of the continent. Temperatures in spring and summer were predominantly below average in the north and above average in the south. Autumn saw above-average mean temperatures over most of the continent; southern France and the Alps were the exception. The Iberian Peninsula was warmer than average in all seasons. The tendency for temperature anomalies to be slightly higher from E-OBS than from ERA-Interim can be clearly seen over Italy and neighbouring countries in winter and autumn.
<br><br>
The winter minimum temperatures (Figure 8, top panels) in southern Europe were more below average (or less above average) than the winter maximum temperatures over the region. Conversely, it was the maximum temperatures (Figure 8, bottom panels) in southern Europe that were the more anomalous in spring and summer. Minimum temperatures were more anomalously warm than maximum temperatures in autumn over the eastern half of the region. In contrast, the Iberian Peninsula experienced relatively high maximum temperatures but relatively low minimum temperatures in autumn.
<br><br>
