<h3 id="seasonprecip">Seasonal precipitation</h3>
During 2017, the season with the largest negative anomaly was the winter, making it the second driest winter in the record in terms of precipitation. The winter season brought much below average precipitation in most of the European region. Exceptions were the Norwegian west coast, with much above average precipitation, and an area south of the Baltic stretching towards the Black Sea with below average precipitation.
<br><br>
During spring, large parts of the European domain remained drier than average, but many regions in the east experienced above average precipitation. Summer and autumn were close to average when averaging over the whole domain, however there were large differences across the domain. During summer, most of northern Europe experienced below-average precipitation, as did the Alpine region and the north of Italy and Slovenia, with a number of heavy rainfall events heavily influencing the average for the season and leading to flash flooding events.
<br><br>
Between the two precipitation datasets there are a couple of disagreements with regard to precipitation anomalies in summer, ERA-Interim show above average rainfall for Greece, whereas E-OBS indicate these areas to be below average. The opposite is true for spring with above average conditions in southeast Europe in E-OBS and blow average in ERA-Interim.
<br><br>
During autumn, the southwest of Europe saw much below average rainfall, whereas the countries along the Adriatic coast, the land areas adjacent to the Baltic Sea, as well as a large area between these two, experienced much above average precipitation. The heavy rainfall along the Adriatic coast, led to large-scale flooding in several regions.
