<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_rr1_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_RR1_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_rr1_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_RR1_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_rr1_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc__2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_rr1_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc__2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 15: RR1: Number of wet days in 2017 (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right). E-OBS v16.0e</em>
<br><br>
The consecutive dry days, which is a metric for the length of the longest dry spell (Figure 16), shows that Europe saw a dry spell which was longer than the 1981-2010 mean value, but the values over Portugal, Spain, Corsica, Sardinia, and other parts of Italy are exceptionally high.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_2017_year_v16_0e_nc__2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_2017_year_v16_0e_nc__2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc__2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_cdd_anom_2017_year_v16_0e_nc__2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 16: CDD: Consecutive dry days in 2017 (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right). E-OBS v16.0e</em>
<br><br>
From the perspective of extreme precipitation, 2017 was at first sight not a remarkable year. The number of heavy precipitation days, where the daily sum of precipitation exceeds 20 mm (Figure 17), for 2017 is close to the 1981-2010 long term mean for the largest part of Europe. Slightly higher values than normal are found along the Atlantic coast of Norway and over the Alpine region and southeast of that. Slightly lower values are found mainly over Scotland, the northwest corner of Spain and in northern Italy. Similarly, the maximum one-day precipitation sum (Figure 18) with respect to the annual value averaged over the 1981-2010 period show isolated patches across Europe with larger than normal values.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_r20mm_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_R20mm_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/2017/Stateofclimate_2017_r20mm_2017_year_v16_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_R20mm_baselayers_overlay_2017-07-01T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
